[h1]Opening a File[/h1]

A file must be opened before you can read from it or write to it. 
Either the [b]ofstream [/b]or [b]fstream [/b]object may be used to open a file for writing.
Let's open a file called "[b]test.txt"[/b] and write some content to it: [code format="cpp"]#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  [b]ofstream [/b]MyFile;
  MyFile.open("test.txt");

  MyFile << "Some text. \n";
}[/code]
The above code creates an [b]ofstream [/b]object called MyFile, and uses the [b]open() [/b]function to open the "test.txt" file on the file system. As you can see, the same stream output operator is used to write into the file.
[note]If the specified file does not exist, the [b]open [/b]function will create it automatically.[/note]

[h1]Closing a File[/h1]

When you've finished working with a file, close it using the member function [b]close()[/b].[code format="cpp" ]#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  ofstream MyFile;
  MyFile.open("test.txt");

  MyFile << "Some text! \n";
  MyFile.[b]close()[/b];
}[/code]
Running this code will cause a "test.txt" file to be created in the directory of your project with "Some text!" written in it.
[note]You also have the option of specifying a path for your file in the [b]open [/b]function, since it can be in a location other than that of your project.[/note]
